Task 1

The gasoline dataset in the pls dataset consists of data on 60 different gasoline samples. For each sample, the near-infra-read (NIR) spectrum has been measured, which consists of measurements at 401 different wavelengths.

library(pls)
data(gasoline)
matplot(seq(900,1700,2),t(gasoline$NIR), type='l', ylab='log(1/R)', xlab='wavelength (nm)')

Also recorded is the octane number of each sample. We will use the NIR measurements to predict the octane number of each sample. Note that here \(n=60\) and \(p=401\), so we have many more covariates than samples.

  1. Start by using the lm command to predict the octane number from the NIR spectra.
gas.lm <- lm(octane~NIR, data=gasoline)

What happens? How many of the coefficients are estimated?

Solution

The covariate matrix \(\mathbf X\) is \(60\times 401\). The naive OLS estimator \[(\mathbf X^\top \mathbf X)^{-1}\mathbf X^\top \mathbf y\] involves the inverse of \((\mathbf X^\top \mathbf X)^{-1}\), which in this case is a \(401 \times 401\) matrix of rank at most 60. Thus it is not invertible.

R deals with this by only using the first 60 covariates, and returns NA for the other \(401-60=341\) coefficients.

  1. We’ll now try principal component regression. First, project the NIR values onto the first 10 principal components. Then build a linear model using lm. Split the data into a training set containing 40 observations, and a test set containing 20 observations. What is the predictive accuracy of your model?
Solution

Before we split the data, let’s just see how we do PCR.

NIR.pca <- prcomp(gasoline$NIR)
PCscores <- NIR.pca$x[,1:10]
gas.pcr <- lm(gasoline$octane~PCscores)

There are 10+1 (including the intercept) estimated PC score coefficients

coef(gas.pcr)
 (Intercept)  PCscoresPC1  PCscoresPC2  PCscoresPC3  PCscoresPC4  PCscoresPC5 
  87.1775000    3.1731758    1.4634333  -12.1953366  -20.6917237    1.6524197 
 PCscoresPC6  PCscoresPC7  PCscoresPC8  PCscoresPC9 PCscoresPC10 
  -0.4649022    0.4379098    0.5110901   -7.8667651   -2.8952053

or converting back to the coefficients of the original variables gives

gas.pcr.coef <- NIR.pca$rotation[,1:10] %*% coef(gas.pcr)[-1]
head(gas.pcr.coef)
            [,1]
900 nm 0.2486964

904 nm 0.3228056

910 nm 0.5084448

If we do the same using the pcr command from the pls package, we find

gas.pcr_pls <- pcr(octane~NIR, data=gasoline, ncomp=10)
head(coef(gas.pcr_pls))

Let’s now split the data into training and test sets.

set.seed(123)
train <- sample(1:60, size=40, replace=FALSE)

# Split the data before doing the PCA
gas.train <- gasoline[train,]
gas.test <- gasoline[-train,]

We will build a model on the training set.

NIR.pca <- prcomp(gas.train$NIR)
PCscores <- NIR.pca$x[,1:10]
train.data <- data.frame(y=gas.train$octane, x=PCscores)
gas.pcr <- lm(y~., data=train.data)
#lm(gas.train$octane~PCscores)

To test the accuracy on the prediction set, requires us to project the test data onto the same PCs (after subtracting the mean)

# project the test data onto the same PCs.

NIR.test.scores <- sweep(gas.test$NIR,2, NIR.pca$center)%*% NIR.pca$rotation[,1:10]

Alternatively, and much easier, we can project new data onto the principal components using the predict function:

test.scores2 <- predict(NIR.pca, gas.test$NIR)[,1:10]
max(abs(test.scores2-NIR.test.scores)) 
[1] 0
## check it agrees with our computation

Finally, we can predict using the computed PC scores for the test data

test.data <- data.frame(x=test.scores2)
(gas.pred <- predict(gas.pcr, newdata=test.data))
       1        2        4       11       16       18       20       22

      30       32       33       34       40       41       46       47 
86.48568 84.35257 84.52605 84.31288 88.42223 88.94907 88.68408 88.47148 
      52       54       55       56 
87.33304 84.95604 85.22641 84.47580

Now we can compute the root mean square prediction error

errors <- gas.pred- gas.test$octane
sqrt(mean((errors)^2))
[1] 0.2519336
  1. Now use the pcr command from the pls package. You can use cross-validation to assess the prediction accuracy, and plot the predictive accuracies, for different number of principal components using the code below. How many principal components would you retain in your model to ensure the best performance?

From this, it looks like 4 components is sufficient. Using more than 4 components doesn’t lead to big decreases in the cross-validation error, and can even result in larger prediction errors.

  1. Now try ridge regression. What value would you choose for the ridge penalty term \(\lambda\)?
Solution 
library(glmnet)
gas.ridge <- glmnet(gasoline$NIR, gasoline$octane, alpha=0)
plot(gas.ridge, xvar='lambda') 

lambdas <- 10^seq(3,-2,by=-0.1)
cv_fit <- cv.glmnet(gasoline$NIR, gasoline$octane, alpha = 0, lambda = lambdas)
plot(cv_fit)

We usually pick \(\lambda\) to be the value which achieves the smallest MSE

cv_fit$lambda.min
[1] 0.2511886

or the largest value of \(\lambda\) that gives a prediction error within one standard deviation of the minimum:

cv_fit$lambda.1se
[1] 1.258925

We can extract the coefficients for a given value of lambda as follows:

coef(glmnet(gasoline$NIR, gasoline$octane, alpha=0, lambda=cv_fit$lambda.1se))

Task 2

The lm command in R will automatically work if you pass in a matrix of response variables. To demonstrate this, lets try to predict the sepal width and sepal length from the petal length and widths for the iris data.

lm(cbind(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width) ~ Petal.Length+Petal.Width, data=iris)

Call:
lm(formula = cbind(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width) ~ Petal.Length + 
    Petal.Width, data = iris)

Coefficients:
              Sepal.Length  Sepal.Width
(Intercept)    4.1906        3.5870    
Petal.Length   0.5418       -0.2571    
Petal.Width   -0.3196        0.3640

Check that the parameter estimates you find are the same as if you did two univariate linear regressions.

Solution
